---
title: "The Ownership Economy: Crypto & The Next Frontier of Consumer Software"
author: "Jesse Walden"
domain: "variant.fund"
url: "https://variant.fund/articles/the-ownership-economy/"
pubDate: 2020-08-07
takeaway: "An influential thesis explaining how user-owned products and protocols can grow faster and align incentives better than centralized alternatives."
---

Jesse Walden's thesis on the "ownership economy" presents a compelling model for alignment between software builders and users. In standard consumer software, there is an inherent lifecycle of exploitation: platforms start by being helpful to attract users, but eventually, they pivot to extraction once they achieve dominant market share. By utilizing cryptographic tokens and decentralized governance, we can align the economic incentives of users and creators from day one, transforming passive consumers into active, incentivized co-owners who directly benefit from the network’s growth.

From an engineering standpoint, this is a radical and exciting architecture. Instead of closed databases and proprietary APIs, we are building on open protocols where data is composable and permissionless. It completely redefines the network effect—instead of being locked in by a single company, users carry their identity and assets across a constellation of interoperable apps. However, as founders, we must cut through the speculative noise. The real challenge is not financial engineering, but building actual, tangible utility and delightful user experiences where decentralized ownership is a feature, not a barrier to entry.

### What stuck with me
- **Incentive alignment model**: Distributing ownership to users turns passive consumers into highly motivated growth vectors.
- **Open composable data**: Open protocols allow developers to build on top of existing data layers without gatekeepers.
- **Utility over speculation**: Decentralized platforms must focus on delivering outstanding product utility rather than just speculative financial incentives.
